  <span id="freeText393200171814455192" style="display:none">This is really about 3.5 stars.<br /><br />I don't like seafood and I don't eat meat, but I love food enough that I hung on every food description Reichl gave, even if it was something I wouldn't eat now (I grew up a meat eater). My automatic inclination was to really like the book, since I love good food and so does the author. <br /><br />It warmed my heart that she disguised herself and saw that many of those in the restaurant business gave far lesser service to those who by their appearance do not seem wealthy or important, and the worst service to those who were women past the flush of youth. <br /><br />I loved her inclusion of her young son, with his enthusiasm, his own tastes, and his comments. <br /><br />This is the first book of Reichl's that I've read, and it won't be the last.</span>
